1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,668
What if I told you that adding a losing asset to your

2
00:00:03,768 --> 00:00:08,716
portfolio could make you more money? Sounds insane. But this is exactly

3
00:00:08,816 --> 00:00:13,623
what modern portfolio theory proves — and it's the reason every hedge

4
00:00:13,723 --> 00:00:18,956
fund on Wall Street obsesses over one number above all others: correlation.

5
00:00:20,056 --> 00:00:25,439
Welcome to QuantiFire. Today we're breaking down the math behind portfolio

6
00:00:25,539 --> 00:00:30,034
diversification — not the hand-wavy don't put all your eggs in

7
00:00:30,134 --> 00:00:34,628
one basket version, but the actual formula quants use to build

8
00:00:34,728 --> 00:00:40,260
multi-billion dollar portfolios. By the end of this video, you'll understand

9
00:00:40,360 --> 00:00:46,189
why two stocks with identical returns can produce completely different portfolio

10
00:00:46,289 --> 00:00:49,524
outcomes depending on how they move together.

11
00:00:51,424 --> 00:00:56,906
The portfolio variance formula has three parts. The first two terms,

12
00:00:57,006 --> 00:01:02,981
shown in blue, capture each asset's individual risk weighted by allocation

13
00:01:03,081 --> 00:01:08,070
— those are fixed once you choose your positions. The critical

14
00:01:08,170 --> 00:01:12,175
third part is the cross term in teal and gold: two

15
00:01:12,275 --> 00:01:18,004
times the weights times the individual volatilities times rho. When rho

16
00:01:18,104 --> 00:01:23,011
is high, this term inflates total portfolio risk. When rho is

17
00:01:23,111 --> 00:01:28,019
low or negative, this term shrinks it. That single number rho

18
00:01:28,119 --> 00:01:32,124
determines whether diversification actually works.

19
00:01:33,224 --> 00:01:38,265
Correlation runs from negative one to positive one. When rho is

20
00:01:38,365 --> 00:01:42,672
plus one, assets move in perfect lockstep — you get no

21
00:01:42,772 --> 00:01:48,956
diversification benefit whatsoever. When rho is zero, the cross term vanishes

22
00:01:49,056 --> 00:01:54,343
and you get the maximum free diversification. When rho is negative

23
00:01:54,443 --> 00:01:59,648
one, assets move in exact opposition — you can actually eliminate

24
00:01:59,748 --> 00:02:02,668
risk entirely with the right weights.

25
00:02:04,268 --> 00:02:09,933
Here is the counterintuitive part. Suppose Asset A returns eight

26
00:02:10,033 --> 00:02:15,158
percent with twenty percent volatility — a Sharpe ratio of

27
00:02:15,258 --> 00:02:20,563
0.40. Asset B returns only four percent with fifteen percent

28
00:02:20,663 --> 00:02:25,788
volatility — a Sharpe of 0.27. By every standalone metric,

29
00:02:25,888 --> 00:02:30,473
Asset B is clearly inferior. It has lower return and

30
00:02:30,573 --> 00:02:35,608
lower Sharpe. A naive investor throws it out immediately.

31
00:02:36,708 --> 00:02:40,549
But if Asset A and Asset B have a correlation of

32
00:02:40,649 --> 00:02:47,363
negative 0.5, combining them fifty-fifty produces a portfolio returning six percent

33
00:02:47,463 --> 00:02:52,536
with only nine percent volatility. That is lower than Asset B's

34
00:02:52,636 --> 00:02:58,530
fifteen percent and dramatically lower than Asset A's twenty percent. The

35
00:02:58,630 --> 00:03:03,702
Sharpe ratio jumps to 0.67 — nearly double Asset A's standalone

36
00:03:03,802 --> 00:03:09,368
number. The weak asset earned its place through negative correlation.

37
00:03:10,468 --> 00:03:16,229
Look at this bar chart. Asset A carries twenty percent volatility. Asset

38
00:03:16,329 --> 00:03:22,905
B fifteen percent. The combined portfolio at negative 0.5 correlation carries only

39
00:03:23,005 --> 00:03:27,790
nine percent volatility — less than half of Asset A and well

40
00:03:27,890 --> 00:03:33,082
below Asset B. This is the free lunch of diversification. You are

41
00:03:33,182 --> 00:03:37,560
not just averaging the risks — you are cancelling them.

42
00:03:41,660 --> 00:03:47,030
Watch what happens as we slide correlation from positive one down

43
00:03:47,130 --> 00:03:51,828
to negative one. At positive one — perfect lockstep — the

44
00:03:51,928 --> 00:03:58,224
portfolio carries seventeen point five percent volatility, which is just the

45
00:03:58,324 --> 00:04:04,116
weighted average of the two assets. As correlation falls, the variance

46
00:04:04,216 --> 00:04:09,418
shrinks. At zero, we hit twelve point five percent. At negative

47
00:04:09,518 --> 00:04:14,889
0.5, nine percent — below both individual assets. And at negative

48
00:04:14,989 --> 00:04:20,865
one, you could construct a portfolio with near-zero volatility. This is

49
00:04:20,965 --> 00:04:24,400
the mathematical proof of diversification.

50
00:04:25,526 --> 00:04:30,700
Now scale this up. In a portfolio of N assets, the covariance

51
00:04:30,800 --> 00:04:35,800
matrix Sigma is an N by N grid of all pairwise correlations

52
00:04:35,900 --> 00:04:42,198
and variances. Portfolio variance becomes w-transpose Sigma w — where w is

53
00:04:42,298 --> 00:04:49,460
your weight vector. The diagonal holds each asset's own variance. Every off-diagonal

54
00:04:49,560 --> 00:04:55,425
entry is a cross term controlled by correlation. This one equation is

55
00:04:55,525 --> 00:05:01,650
the foundation of every optimizer from Markowitz's 1952 paper to the 500

56
00:05:01,750 --> 00:05:05,194
billion dollar quant funds running today.

57
00:05:06,294 --> 00:05:11,399
But here is the critical trap. Correlation is not stable. In

58
00:05:11,499 --> 00:05:17,992
normal markets, correlations between different asset classes run from 0.2 to

59
00:05:18,092 --> 00:05:21,895
0.45 — shown in teal. But in a crisis — 2008,

60
00:05:21,995 --> 00:05:27,100
March 2020 — correlations spike toward 0.9 and above — shown

61
00:05:27,200 --> 00:05:33,345
in red. Everything sells off together. The diversification you relied on

62
00:05:33,445 --> 00:05:39,244
disappears exactly when you need it most. This is called correlation

63
00:05:39,344 --> 00:05:44,102
breakdown, and it is one of the hardest problems in risk

64
00:05:44,202 --> 00:05:52,776
management. Solutions include stress-testing with crisis-period correlations, and adding assets with

65
00:05:52,876 --> 00:05:59,282
structurally negative correlation like volatility products and tail hedges.

66
00:06:01,028 --> 00:06:05,861
Your action item: next time you build a portfolio, don't just

67
00:06:05,961 --> 00:06:11,764
look at expected returns. Pull the correlation matrix. Identify your most

68
00:06:11,864 --> 00:06:17,264
correlated pairs — those are your concentration risk. Then ask: what

69
00:06:17,364 --> 00:06:22,439
can I add that lowers those correlations? That question is worth

70
00:06:22,539 --> 00:06:25,432
more than chasing the next hot asset.

